>I just wrote a patch that adds simple cursor configurability to fvwm
>with a CursorConfig command.  The patch is against 2.0.43, so it
>may be slightly outdated, but it should probably patch fine.

I don't need it because I haven't thought about cursors, but it
were nice if you added an option to your patch to use default
X root window cursor for fvwm windows- our system sets normal 
lefty cursor as default on startup and it seems a bit stupid 
that fvwm uses almost same cursor as system but not right so,
it's not same one.

Off the topic cursor, still interesting:

I wrote you some words about our fvwm2 configuration system a couple
of weeks ago. We have been talking about making a de facto fvwm2 
configuration system to allow root modify settings, still alloving
users to modify whatever they want. Those files I said you could 
look at are now obsolete, I've rewritten all our system fvwm files.
It's now about 5x faster than reading M4 parsed files and overall
design is much cleaner. 

My design is simple: /usr/local/bin/fvwm2 is a shell script which 
checks if user has fvwm2 files already installed and installs defaults 
if necessary. All users have directory .fvwm2 and this directory is
created if it doesn't exist. There are following system files:
  menus: defines default menus
  key_bindings: defines default key bindings
  style_templates: defines default decor and style parameters
  styles: defines which decor and style groups to use for each window
  icons: defines icons to use with windows
  iconboxes: defines where to put all icons
  functions: defines all system default function
Users get files menus, key_bindings, styles, icons, functions and fvwmrc
to their new directory .fvwm2 from /usr/local/share/fvwm2/default. fvwm2
script is started to parse $HOME/.fvwm2/fvwmrc, which reads users own
files, and these files read by default system files. User can remove
all files and make his own $HOME/.fvwm2/fvwmrc ignoring all system
defaults, or he can read what he wants from system files and make his
own modifications in .fvwm2 files.

When making this change wanted a new feature to fvwm2. I would like
to define in Fvwm.tmpl a variable for settings files, like 
FvwmSetupDir blaablaa
We have many different unix variants with same fvwm2 setup files and
it's a dirty hack to try to use same setup files from lib dir for
system dependent libraries directory. I suggest we add a new variable
for setup files which defaults to InstallDir/share/fvwm2, whatever
InstallDir is. Maybe we should really have another variable InstallBase
and install all other directories under that, like
InstallDir /usr/local
FvwmBinDir $InstallDir/bin
FvwmDir $InstallDir/lib/fwwm2
FvwmLibDir $InstallDir/lib
FvwmSetupDir $InstallDir/share/fvwm2

	* hile *
	   
